CloudWatch versus CloudTrail versus Config, picking the right tool.

The three observability services overlap in casual conversation but answer distinct questions, and this is the map worth memorising. Is my C-P-U high, is my Lambda erroring, are requests slow? That's CloudWatch, performance and health. Who deleted that S3 bucket, who changed this I-A-M policy at three fourteen in the morning? That's CloudTrail, the A-P-I audit log. What did my security group look like last Tuesday, and was it compliant? That's Config, configuration history plus rules.

They also compose into standard patterns. Alert me when R-D-S C-P-U stays above eighty percent for ten minutes: a CloudWatch alarm on the R-D-S metric. Alert me when someone calls DeleteTrail: CloudTrail delivers to CloudWatch Logs, a metric filter catches it, and an alarm fires. Alert me when an S3 bucket becomes publicly accessible: the Config rule s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited notifying S-N-S. Automatically fix a non-compliant security group: a Config rule plus S-S-M Automation remediation. Get in-operating-system E-C-2 memory or application logs: the CloudWatch Agent. And watch the A-W-S bill: a billing alarm on EstimatedCharges in us-east-one.

The mnemonic that carries the whole module. CloudWatch is how is it doing, metrics, logs, alarms, and dashboards. CloudTrail is who did what, every A-P-I call, retained and searchable. And Config is what changed and is it compliant, a configuration timeline with rules and remediation. And they compose: CloudTrail records an action and a metric filter turns it into a CloudWatch alarm; Config finds drift and S-S-M Automation fixes it.
